This paper is likely to belong to the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it discusses the use of latent features learned by deep learning approaches for machine learning. It also involves clustering instances and their relations, which is a common technique in machine learning. 

It could also belong to cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as the use of latent features is a common technique in AI. 

The paper also discusses the interpretation of latent features, which could place it in the category of cs.DB (Databases) as interpretation is an important aspect of database management. 

The use of clustering could also place it in the category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as clustering is a common technique in natural language processing. 

Finally, the paper discusses the redundancy of latent features, which could place it in the category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) as redundancy is an important aspect of security.
